6 which the name of the member appears;
7 Sec. 2. 4 MRSA §1201, sub-§8-A is enacted to read:
8 8-A. Duly acknowledged. "Duly acknowledged" means acknowledged pursuant to
9 chapter 39 or through an electronic identification process designated in a rule established
10 by the board of trustees.
11 Sec. 3. 4 MRSA §1201, sub-§19-A is enacted to read:
12 19-A. Survive or surviving. "Survive" or "surviving" means to live, by clear and
13 convincing evidence, for at least 120 hours after the death of the qualifying member or
14 family member, as applicable.
15 Sec. 4. 4 MRSA §1201, sub-§20, as enacted by PL 1989, c. 133, §20, is amended
16 to read:
17 20. Surviving spouse. "Surviving spouse" means the spouse alive at the time of who
18 survives the death of the member or former member.
19 Sec. 5. 4 MRSA §1305-A, sub-§1, ¶B, as enacted by PL 2007, c. 137, §7, is
20 amended to read:
21 B. Payment must be made after termination of service and not less than 22 days nor
22 more than 60 days after receipt of the application and receipt of the last payroll upon
23 which the name of the member appears;
24 Sec. 6. 4 MRSA §1353, sub-§1-A, ¶A, as amended by PL 2007, c. 491, §49, is
25 further amended to read:
26 A. A member with less than 5 years of continuous creditable service immediately
27 preceding an application for a disability allowance that member's last date of service is
28 not eligible for that a disability retirement allowance if that disability is the result of a
29 physical or mental condition which that existed prior to the person's latest membership
30 in a retirement program of the Maine Public Employees Retirement System, unless the
31 disability is a result of, or has been substantially aggravated by, an injury or accident
32 received in the line of duty.
33 Sec. 7. 4 MRSA §1353, sub-§5, as amended by PL 2007, c. 491, §51, is further
34 amended to read:
35 5. Earnings. The chief executive director officer may require each disability
36 beneficiary to submit an annual statement of earnings received from any gainful occupation
37 during that year. For any year during which the total of those earnings and the disability
38 allowance exceeds the current salary of the position that the disabled beneficiary last held,
39 the excess must be deducted from any disability retirement allowance payments made to
40 the beneficiary during the next calendar year. These deductions are prorated on a monthly
41 basis, in an equitable manner prescribed by the board of trustees, over the year or part of
